column17:
Was the participant aware of the goal?
1= YES  0 = NO
column18: Transcribe the written answer of each participant's guess  of the study's goal.

I think the purpose of this experiment was to study how people with physical disabilities would go about tasks such as writing. I did not quite understand where the cartoon and rating them had to do with that though. Maybe to see that moving facial muscles due to smilitng or laughter would affect holding the pen in the correct position.

The purpose of the experiment was to see how well you can use other parts of your body besides your hand the purpose of the cartoons was to see maybe how well you focused on the cartoons even though you were trying to multitsak with the pen in your mouth.
I think the purpose of this experiment was to see how we as humans adapt to not being able to use certain parts of our bodies to complete tasks.
To test the ability of students to complete everyday, "normal" tasks in a different way.

I think the purpose of this experiment (having read the pourpose we were given on the sheet form- my purpose may be so off...), was to see how having certain disabilities may affect humor or what that person finds funny.
I assumed it had to do with physical ability and methods of making every-day life easier for those who might be physically disabled, but maybe its something else!
I think the purpose is to see how well people can use alterate ways to do daily tasks.

I believe that the purpose of this experiment was to test how difficult it would be for someone to do an everyday activitiy in a different way.  I believe that it was trying to test how quickly someone could do something they do everyday, write, in a strange and different way for them.

I think that the purpose of this experiment is to show how difficult it is to perform simple tasks with a part of the body that does not usually perform that task. Although one may be able to draw a straight line with their hand very easily, it is much more difficult when the task is done with the mouth.
To demonstrate the feasibility of using other body parts to do the same function as other body parts normally would.

Test how able participants are to adapting to being forced to use different body parts than visual in simple tasks (other wise). Additionally, seeing how able participants are to focusing on cartoons while still being in the uncomfortable position of having a pen in their mouths.
If were focusing too much on our discomfort, we may not be as ammused by something as we would have been otherwise.
How well do the participants in holding the pen in the correct position with their mouths before watch the acrto0ons and after.
To see levels of frustration or humor when performing tasks with body parts you wouldnt normally use.
To examine if the muscles in our mouth were primed enough to do the tasks our brain was telling them to do, even though they were unusual tasks.
It seems to me that the purpose is to judge the ability to use different body parts that we normally do not use to complete.
To cmplete daily tasks in a manner that is unusual but normal for those who are physically impaired.
If using parts of the body not normally used for certain tasks will require extra attention and take away from the understanding of visual stimuli.
How people adapt to using different parts of the body for daily tasks.

The purpose of this experiment was to test an individuals motor skills used uncommonly with different body parts. So in other words this experiment tested how well we can do specific actions that we usely use common body parts with uncommon body parts. ex. writing with your mouth instead of with your hands.
The purpose is to see how different tasks are easier or harder than offers based on the particular impairment of holding a pen in ones mouth.
To see if using different parts of body and having to concentrate on task can change a humor level.

The purpose of this experiment is to do certain tasks with body parts you normally wouldnt do them with. Also to find better/cheaper ways to technologies to aid people that have disabilities and cant use appropriate body parts for certain tasks.
I think the purpose of this experiment may be to see how ability would affect whether we are amused by the cartoons.
To attempt performing tasks with my mouth that I would normallly do with my hands, and see how successful my performance was. I dont understand the cartoon part.
I believe the purpose of the experiment was to see how difficult using alternative methods to perform everyday tasks can be (like for the handicapped) and how multitasking adds to this difficulty.

understand what tasks can be done with other parts of the body that you normally wouldnt complete the task with.  If someon is disablesd, maybe that persona can do certain tasks with another part of their body that they normally would not be able to do.
To see how difficult it would be to learn how touse this method to write
To test a different form of writing that may be used by those who are disabled or for further assistive technology.

I think the purpose of this experiment is to see peoples reactions to the cartoons while focusing on an uncomfortable tasl. And explore if they have less understanding of the cartoons while holding a pen in their mouth.
The purpose was to see how easy or difficult it is for people with a physical impairment to live day to day. It made me appreciate my hands a lot more.
I believe the purpose of this experiment is to test the ease that disabled people can accomplish a task that we go through every day, never really knowing quite how difficult it actually is for them.

The purpose of this experiment was to get a feel and understand what it is like to use parts of the body we dont regularly use for a certain (?) to carry out tasks. This simulates how physically impaired people are able to carry out some tasks.

I think the purpose was to see how much harder it was to hold the pen when I had to think about what I was doing.  Could different pictures make it easier or harder depending on how I felt about them?
To examine the ability of an individual to hald a pen and show a response by writing with the pen in the mouth, maybe to see if certain emotions bring better coordination.
Test peoples ability to follow directions and in the case of the cartoons focus on two very different things at once.
I think the purpose was to give participants a feel of what it feels like to be physically unable to perform certain tasks properly and to get a feel of what the physically impaired may feel like.
I believe the purpose of this exam was to see how successful one was at doing a task with a different body part than normal and also how different levels of arousal can affect the outcome.
The purpose is to exemplify how difficult it can be to complete tasks when you dont use the body parts you are used to using for that given task.
To see if our amusement level effects our control of the pen in our mouth.

To see how difficult it is to use non-traditional ways to complete a task. How one's mood is affected after struggling to complete a task. Essentially gaging whether a disability can affect outlook, mood, attitude.
To see my mood/emotions/ability to find something comedic while physically uncomfortable.

I think the purpose of this experiment was to see how different people are able to perform different tasks using unusual parts of their body.  The humor aspect may play in because different pople react to different comedic scenes different, and there may be a correlation between humor scores and success of task completion.
As someone who has a grandfather who is paralyzed on his right side, I believe this experiment is helping to find ways for people like him to engage in everyday tasks.

I think the purpose of the experiment was to test whether positioning oneself in an unusual/possible uncomfortable task performing condition affects the person's perception/opinion of cartoons based on understanding differences between people. While testing whether I performed well in holding the pen in the correct position you also tested if my opinion of my performance affects my perception/opinion on images that I would "normally" perceive as amusing
To test how well people can do everyday tasks such as writing without using normal body parts.

To see the capability level/difficulty of someone using one body part for a task they primarilly rely on another body part for. To test how dependent an individual is on their hands/if drastically varies between participants.

To show the difficulty of someone who does not have "normal" physical characteristics and their daily struggles and how they must use orther methods to perform basic tasks.  I think there is something else involved as the purpose but I can't figure it out.
To study whether amusement is affected by some degree of discomfort.
To see how tough it is to writhe w/ the pen in your mouth & to see if you get better over time w/ more practice at holding the pen in your mouth
I think the purpose of the experiment was to see how well we did adapting to doing a task in a different way and how much practice with it helped.

The purpose of this experioment was to observe peoples ability to use other parts of their body, like the mouth, to do something that the hands would normall do. This could then be applied to products that can be made to help people who dont have use of their hands preform tasks lke writing.
To distract me with task but still trying to focus on the right pen position and completing them as stated.
I think the experiment was about demonstrations the alternative ways that people with disabilities have in order to complete normal tasks.
The purpose of this experiment is to judge the bailities of using writing utensils in various ways. It explores the challenges of the disabled.

I think the purpose is to examine different means of accomplishing relatively easy tasks when faced with relatively major setbacks. I'm not entirely sure how the cartoons connected to the act of holding the pen.
To find alternative ways for disabled people since the old alternatives are really expensive and many people cannot afford it.

To observe the difficuluty or ease of using a not hand body part to write, which generally is a hand task.  I'm unsure about the cartoons, potentially the circling was neater when i was more amused, but I do not know!
Possiblly something to do with discomfort and humor.
The purpose of this experiment is to see how well participants can perform tasks using atypical parts of their body associated with said tasks. This could help impaired individuals in the future.
Probably not as much about the pen being in ones mouth as much as how one responds to the cartoons
To test amusement or comprehension wile performing an usual task.
To observe how well you adapted to writing with your mouth by the end of the experiment.

I think the purpose of this experiment is to demonstrate the difficulty of using your body parts to perform unusual tasks and to determine how some things should be designed to lessen those difficulties.
To see if these alternative methods are reasonable solutions for those who have disabilities and cant function normally in all aspects of daily life.
To see if there was any connection between disabilities/impairment and not finding stuff amusing.
The purpose of this experiment is to understand coordination skills of parts of our body that are not used to perform certain abilities.
To practice using an unfamiliar body part to complete simple tasks
To gain a better understanding of the difficulties disabled people have so we can better create methods and technologies that will better assist these individuals.
To see how we can adapt to a change in our basic functioning like loosing an arm.

The purpose of this experiment is to evaluate small tasks done with a typical body parts. The research here tells us some things about using atypical body parts and how we can use that to help people who are paralyzed/handicapped/etc. to perform tasks with atypical body parts as I did in this experiment.
To see if you can do an annoying/difficult task and see if it affects your mood/how amused you are by the cartoons.
To test our ability to perform tasks using body parts we would not normally use to perform these tasks.
To analyze how a novice can adapt to performing tasks in a way they would not usually perform them. Also to assess the usefullness of this strategy.
I think the purpose was to demonstrate how accurate using another part of the body can make a task less effective and how with practice you can slightly improve.

To see how efficient (or inseficient) other body parts are at doing certain tasks that they usually do not do, thus displaying the need for research in technology to help handicapped people perform every day tasks.
Test how well the brain functions while performing tasks with body parts we are not used to using.
I think the purpose of this experiment is to help people become aware of what it is like to live with physical impairments, and how hard it can be for them to compensate
To see if I would indicate my ratings while still holding the pen in my mouth.
To understand the experience of individuals who have aphysical impairments in completing tasks in their everyday lives, many of which we take for granted to have the ability to complete so easily
To examine ways in which impaired individuals may be able to improve their mobility of their bodies in other ways to live a full life.

The purpose of this experiment may be to see how manipulating motor skills affects emotion. If someone is concentrating on an unconventional, frustrating task, how would normal emotions/reactions to other stimuli be affected?
The purpose of this experiment is to test how we would handle some tasks using ways that we are not good at.
Purpose of this experiment was to see if people can use a different body part to do something they don't normally do it with while focusing also on something else.
The purpose is to observe doing tasks with body parts you aren't used to using. The purpose is to see this success rate and compare it to the level of humor.
To demonstrate how hard it is when you can't use your hands to write and the difficulty of not being understood like other people can.
I think it was looking at how difficult it is to use your mouth to perform every day functions such as writing.

I think the purpose of this is to demonstrate how physically demanding specific impairments are in addition to study the ability of non-impared participants to perform the every day tasks of someone who is impaired.

It gives participants a glimpse at how dual-tasks can be difficult for people who are not used to performing tasks with alternate parts of the body, and shows how people who are not impaired lack some of the required skills of those who are impaired.
To see how challenging it is to write without hands and instead write with your mouth.  To see if advanced more expensive technology is needed for people to write without hands.
To see if the person got any better at using the pen in circuling the numbers on the scale as the experiment went on.

I feel that this experiment is examining how able bodied individuals work with simulations and aids for the disabled. I imagine since we all would prefer to use our hands this can be challenging. I know I sometimes counted things as complete when if I did that with my hand I wouldn't count it at all.
To evaluate how well we can perform everyday tasks in a nontypical way. There are many people out there with disabilities who cannot perform these simple tasks that we take for granted.
To better understand how people feel using different parts of our body than usual to perform certain tasks.
To look into the process of those who are disabled. i.e. using a pen with no hands and seeing if their processing of info is different. (cartoons)

The cartoon poirtion kinda threw off y orginial guess.  If I had to guess now though I would say it has soething to do w/ handling failure of some sort.  We the participants are not meant to do well in the first 3 trials but our response to the cartoons in the wake of repeated failures is the important part.
I think the purpose was to explore alternative routes to help handicap people achieve success completing everyday tasks and based on these results of this would be a possible good method
Like maybe amusement stuff helps people to relax so that it will be easier for them to hold a pen with their mouth to finish tasks.
To observe how people without disabilities perform in these tasks vs how people with disabilities do.
I think it has something to do with how funny we find things when we are frustrated/completing tasks.
I think the purpose of this experiment is to see which task we focused more on. The assigned task or holding the pen in your mouth the correct way.

I believe that the purpose of this experiment was to see the ability to which a person can perform routine tasks like using a pen under the limitations that they cannot use their hands. this was conducted to convey the struggles of those who are physically impaired in their hands to complete this type of task, and to study how much the brain controls our writing without signals sent to our hands.
Alternative ways to complete basic tasks with out the use of your hands. This would especially be helpful for handicap people.
To see how effectively tasks can be performed in atypical ways.
To see if basic functions can be performed by body parts that may not typically be used.
The purpose of this experiment is to determine alternative methods of using objects that are low-cut and easy to learn.
How well people adjust to do certain tasks using body parts that they are not used to and how they feel about using other parts.

To test how people did while doing tasks that they normally wouldn't do (write/draw with a pen in their mouth).  This was to test how people with physical impairments might be affected psychologically as well.
I think the purpose of this experiment is to see how different people can complete tasks, such as writing, if they do not have use of the body parts people typically use for those tasks.
To show people can use their mouths for tasks when physically impaired.
By assessing people doing tasks with the body parts that are not normally used and their perception ability, help people who have disabilities to better perform tasks with equipment.

I think the purpose is to determine the difficulty people have in performing a task with a body part they would not normally use. I think this will be used to determine what might make this task easier for someone so that now technology can hopefully be created to help people with disabilities.
I think the purpose was to see how comfortable I was holding/using the pen in a different way than I normally do.

This experiment simulated a situation in which I couldnt use the body part that i normally would for a task then rated if it increased my sympathy for disabled people by seeing if it decreased my amusement of the cartoons that make fun of disable people.

In order to undetstand if there are more effective and cheaper alternatives to expensive technology (like keyboards that respond to brain waves), it is necessary to test participants doing tasks such as these. With practice, using your teeth to write could possibly become a useful way to write for those who coannot do so in a conventional manner.
The purpose is to test our motor skills doing tasks with our mouth that we wouldnt ordinarilly perform with our mouth.
To see how people handle situations physically at a disadvantage.

For individuals to understand how difficult it is to do tasks in ways they don't normally do them. Additionally to compare someone who doesn't have conditions where they would need to use other body parts to do tasks to those who do.
To demonstrate the difficulty/frustration that disabled people may experience while trying to do simple tasks with body parts that aren't used to being used in that way.
How mood or outlook on life plays a role in motor function.
Create some technology where a person uses their mouth to control it?
To see if holding the pen in our unusual way affects how you think of things.

The purpose of this experiment, I believe, was to see how people can complete tasks using parts of their body they are not used to. ie. your mouth instead of your hand. Also, to see how people adjust when given a task they are not used to, ie. how they hold thier paper or if they use their tongue to help them control the pen.
The purpose seemed to be to see if instead of using technology to help us adapt to our impairments, we can simply use our bodies.
Testing how people can write with their mouth if it is a viable way to write for people who cant use hands.  also maybe testing how people respond to the instructions.
To determine how well people can use their mouth to write
I think the purpose of this experiment was to see the accuracy and ability to correctly write with a pen in your mouth.
The purpose was to see how difficult it is to do everyday tasks with parts of the body you wouldnt typically use.
Possibly to see how people who cannot use their hands to write could function using a different part of their body to do that task.

I think the purpose of this experiment was to test motor function, doing activities normall done with hands with a part rarley used for such function like the mouth. Study may help with research concerning handicapped people who are missing limbs (arms, legs etc.).
To help preliminary research on tools and their use or disabled persons.
The purpose of this experiment is to see how easy/hard it is to do daily functions with an impairment
To see the comfortability and performance in comleting a task in an unusual way than wone is used to.
I think the purpose of this experiment is to help find cheap easy ways of helping people with physical disabilities do things that people that dont have those disabilities, but do them differently.
To understand how succesfully normal people do the tasks in the way people have improvement do.

The purpose of this experiment is to test how one can adopt to new actions. I'm assuming its to see how one can teach themselves to adapt to a new circumstance, ie. not being able to write with one's hands.
Test our psychomotor abilities when asked to do a task in a unusual fashion and process if it has any affect on our cognition.
Measure the ability of people to utilize unordinarilly used body parts to carry our simple tasks.

To test how well participants do using unusual, untrained body parts for specific tasks that are commonly carried our by different muscle groups, parts of the body. My guess would be that this has something to do with comparing motor skills in participants to have learned to carry out this "unusual" technique.
I think it was to see how funny we foudn the cartoons when our mouth was already in a turned up/smiling position.
Examine how physical impairment affects simple tasks like drawing, writing etc.
The purpose is to evaluate the difficulty of performing tasks using body parts that we do not usually use, see what kind of complications occur.
To test how difficult it is to draw diffrent shapes when holding pen in your mouth instead of your hand.
The purpose is to look at how difficult itis to perform tasks with atypical body parts. To see if using your mouth to write with is a good solution if someone cant use their hands.
To test other body parts and their ability to perform tasks that they normally would not.
I think it is to test how we can use different body parts for things we normally dont use, and maybe how we can perform them while our brain is focusing on something else (like a cartoon).
Has something to do with coordination level. Not sure how cartoons relate to purpose.
To see how impaired peoples motor abilities compare to non impaired

I think the purpose of the experiment is to see if we can perform a task using a mehod we are not used to and to see if it impairs our ability to fully comprehend what we are doing/looking at (ie. the cartoons).
No clue
To test to see how individuals performed the tasks and also o see how enjoyable cartoons were while having an uncomfortable situation.

To see how people adapt to doing every day tasks with unusual body parts. I think the point of the cartoons was to test if people were less amused as the continued because they were more frustrated with using their mouth to write.
To test focus while performing an unnatural task?

At this point im not too sure, but it may have had to do with how funny I rated the cartoons with a pen in my mouth. Theres probably a control group out there somewhere who rated it without a pen in their mouth...
The purpose was to investigate a cheap altrenative to writing for those that are not physically able to use their hands.
To either see if we follow the directions when nobody is watching in person or to see if we are struggling, if that affects our attitude/behavior on wheter or not something is funny

The purpose of this experiment is to determine if the mouth, specifically the teeth, can be used to perform a task that is usually completed with your fingers.  This experiment will help determine alternative ways to write for people who cannot use their hands.
I think the purpose of this experiment was to see how well the participants could use the pen to write with their mouths instead of their hands.
The purpose of this experiment is to see what tasks can be carried out easily by using alternative body parts.  This way, possible solutions for those with disabilities can be found.
To test to see how well regular people are able to write with their mouths.
